why question then

00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:42.040
informs where we stand today.

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:45.510
The reaction to Trump
running, the reaction

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:48.400
to other candidates, what
buttons are being pushed.

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:51.490
And so when the immigration
button is being pushed,

00:10:51.490 --> 00:10:54.400
they're really pushing
a different button.

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:56.500
When you have the whole
issue of globalism.

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.990
That's another
button being pushed.

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:01.455
No one talks about how
technology has changed the game

00:11:01.455 --> 00:11:04.350
or how automation has wiped out
significant numbers of jobs.

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:05.530
Oh, no no.

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:07.030
Send those folks back to Mexico.

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:08.820
That's why we don't
have our jobs.

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:10.210
Those are buttons being pushed.

00:11:10.210 --> 00:11:13.090
I just think that we have
to go much deeper when

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:14.615
we start talking
about why people

00:11:14.615 --> 00:11:17.320
are responding the way
they respond politically.

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:18.730
EDDIE HUANG: And
also immigration

00:11:18.730 --> 00:11:20.210
is a boon to the economy.

00:11:20.210 --> 00:11:23.230
It always has, if you
study immigration patterns.

00:11:23.230 --> 00:11:27.220
Even Buffalo, New York did not
have an increase in population

00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:29.470
since I believe the 1950s.

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:32.470
In the last few years,
it has the most--

00:11:32.470 --> 00:11:35.950
it's like the fourth largest
growing city in America

00:11:35.950 --> 00:11:37.480
is Buffalo, New York.

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:39.670
And a lot of it is
immigrants coming

00:11:39.670 --> 00:11:43.240
from Africa and the Middle
East, creating businesses.

00:11:43.240 --> 00:11:44.650
You look at--

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:47.060
I believe it's
Deerfield, Michigan--

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:49.810
it's a very strong
Middle Eastern community.

00:11:49.810 --> 00:11:52.330
Immigrants coming America,
they create businesses,

00:11:52.330 --> 00:11:55.120
they become customers,
they become landowners.

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:58.260
And it's a boon to the country.

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:02.110
ROLAND MARTIN: But the
history, though, shows those.

00:12:02.110 --> 00:12:05.620
When you have
economic anxieties,

00:12:05.620 --> 00:12:09.409
there always is a tendency
I need to blame somebody.

00:12:09.409 --> 00:12:11.200
EDDIE HUANG: And that's
a social construct.

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:12.940
That is a narrative
that white people

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:15.980
who are afraid of the
dispossession of their country,

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:18.870
they create that narrative
that it's Mexicans taking jobs.

00:12:18.870 --> 00:12:21.400
It's immigrants taking jobs.

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:24.610
Immigrants fill jobs that normal
second and third-generation

00:12:24.610 --> 00:12:26.480
Americans, they
don't want to take.

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:28.030
They don't need to take.

00:12:28.030 --> 00:12:30.100
This is the new
workforce coming in,

00:12:30.100 --> 00:12:33.310
whether it's building the
railroads, reconstruction,

00:12:33.310 --> 00:12:35.110
the Panama Canal, the gold rush.

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:38.070
It was always immigrants coming
in and filling these jobs.

00:12:38.070 --> 00:12:41.680
VINT CERF: So could I just
make an observation about this?

00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:44.370
This entire country is
nothing but immigrants.

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:45.690
ROLAND MARTIN: Vint, you're
on the panel for observation.

00:12:45.690 --> 00:12:46.773
You don't have to tell me.

00:12:49.314 --> 00:12:51.230
You're saying you want
to make an observation.

00:12:51.230 --> 00:12:52.240
EDDIE HUANG: I agree with you.

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:53.240
ROLAND MARTIN: Go ahead.

00:12:53.240 --> 00:12:53.741
Go ahead.

00:12:53.741 --> 00:12:54.490
VINT CERF: No, no.

00:12:54.490 --> 00:12:56.180
I just wanted to make
that observation,

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:59.750
that this entire country
is nothing but immigrants.

00:12:59.750 --> 00:13:01.420
That's where we all came from.

00:13:01.420 --> 00:13:04.660
In fact, we displaced the
folks who were here before,

00:13:04.660 --> 00:13:05.890
which is another big issue.

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:08.740
EDDIE HUANG: Before they were
Mexicans, before there was--

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:10.740
PAOLA MENDOZA: The Irish,
before it was Chinese,

00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:11.750
before it was Japanese.

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:13.625
EDDIE HUANG: Italian,
Irish, or Jewish people

00:13:13.625 --> 00:13:15.880
were treated the
way that a lot of us

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:18.750
are treated now,
maybe not as badly.

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:21.130
But like there was
always another.

00:13:21.130 --> 00:13:23.380
There was always a
new immigration group.

00:13:23.380 --> 00:13:24.590
There was always another.

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:26.840
PAOLA MENDOZA: So the reality
is, just off that point,

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:30.220
I think that from the
2008 economic collapse,

00:13:30.220 --> 00:13:31.990
cities that had the
most immigration

00:13:31.990 --> 00:13:34.630
population were the ones
that actually responded--

00:13:34.630 --> 00:13:37.930
rebounded economically
better than other cities.

00:13:37.930 --> 00:13:42.490
And our reality here
is, where we are today,

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:44.620
is to be an immigrant--
the existence

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:47.920
of an immigrant really at this
moment in time is to resist.

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:50.980
My existence as an immigrant
born in Colombia, here

00:13:50.980 --> 00:13:53.680
in the United States for
the majority of my life

00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:56.240
is one of resistance
because, again,

00:13:56.240 --> 00:13:59.350
the political structure,
power structure, power vacuum

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:00.440
that we're in.

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:05.260
And on top of that, the idea
of undocumented immigrants

00:14:05.260 --> 00:14:05.880
is even--

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:10.592
we see what was going on
yesterday in Texas with SB4

00:14:10.592 --> 00:14:12.550
and the protests that
were there and that there

00:14:12.550 --> 00:14:15.512
were actual fights between state
representatives on the floor,

00:14:15.512 --> 00:14:17.470
and they were threatening--
one was threatening

00:14:17.470 --> 00:14:19.000
to shoot another one.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.060
He said that he called
ICE on protesters.

00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:24.370
And so that is the political
climate where we are.

00:14:24.370 --> 00:14:27.310
And I truly believe
that we're there

00:14:27.310 --> 00:14:30.032
because actually we are
unable to communicate

00:14:30.032 --> 00:14:30.740
with one another.

00:14:30.740 --> 00:14:34.510
We are unable to reach
across the aisle, whatever

00:14:34.510 --> 00:14:36.811
that aisle is, and see what
is happening with someone

00:14:36.811 --> 00:14:37.810
that thinks differently.

00:14:37.810 --> 00:14:40.049
Now, having a conversation
obviously is not--

00:14:40.049 --> 00:14:41.590
I'm not saying to
have a conversation

00:14:41.590 --> 00:14:45.830
is allowing for oppression
and for oppressive thoughts

00:14:45.830 --> 00:14:49.270
to be legitimized but to
actually just sit down

00:14:49.270 --> 00:14:52.330
with someone and say let's
break down the facts.

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:54.220
Let's break down the
history of this country

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:56.290
and talk about immigration
and talk about race

00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:58.609
and see where we are and
see where we've been.

00:14:58.609 --> 00:15:00.400
And so where are we
going to go and how are

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:01.340
we going to break the cycle?

00:15:01.340 --> 00:15:02.440
But we're not doing
that at this moment.

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:04.180
ROLAND MARTIN:
Except when you're

00:15:04.180 --> 00:15:05.950
defining things by fake news.

00:15:05.950 --> 00:15:09.860
But you mentioned something
there when you said resist.

00:15:09.860 --> 00:15:11.110
So the question I have--

00:15:11.110 --> 00:15:16.870
OK, resist is one thing,
to get what is another.

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:22.090
So I can look at Montgomery
Improvement Association taking

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:25.270
place December 1st after
Emmett Till is killed.

00:15:25.270 --> 00:15:29.140
And then I see this move in
the Black Freedom Movement,

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:31.600
this quest for freedom.

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:34.750
But resist is one thing.

00:15:34.750 --> 00:15:36.910
To get what?

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:38.539
See because that's vital.

00:15:38.539 --> 00:15:39.330
PAOLA MENDOZA: Yes.

00:15:39.330 --> 00:15:42.340
ROLAND MARTIN: You can resist,
then it's OK I've resisted.

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:46.650
But what the hell am I trying
to get with my resistance?

00:15:46.650 --> 00:15:48.550
EDDIE HUANG: You know
I had a women's studies

00:15:48.550 --> 00:15:51.050
professor in college break it
down for me, Dr. [INAUDIBLE]..

00:15:51.050 --> 00:15:53.800
She said, you know, what
I want in this world is

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:56.890
the same opportunity for the
same job for the same pay

00:15:56.890 --> 00:15:58.017
for the same work.

00:15:58.017 --> 00:15:59.600
And I was like, that
makes some sense.

00:15:59.600 --> 00:16:01.270
And in terms of
resistance, the thing

00:16:01.270 --> 00:16:03.580
I always think
about resisting is

00:16:03.580 --> 00:16:06.430
Americans have to resist this
idea that the country belongs

00:16:06.430 --> 00:16:08.320
to one dominant cultural group.

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:11.110
It doesn't belong to one
dominant cultural group.

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:13.690
The country belongs to
this idea that there

00:16:13.690 --> 00:16:16.450
can be a land in
this world founded

00:16:16.450 --> 00:16:18.880
on equality, freedom
of expression,

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:20.670
and multiculturalism.

00:16:20.670 --> 00:16:21.145
ROLAND MARTIN: But
stop right there.

00:16:21.145 --> 00:16:21.500
EDDIE HUANG: That
is the idea that--

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:23.624
ROLAND MARTIN: I got
something right there, though.

00:16:23.624 --> 00:16:28.327
You said a nation
founded on equality.

00:16:28.327 --> 00:16:29.285
LUVVIE AJAYI: The idea.

00:16:29.285 --> 00:16:30.201
EDDIE HUANG: The idea.

00:16:30.201 --> 00:16:31.368
ROLAND MARTIN: But-- no, no.

00:16:31.368 --> 00:16:32.367
PAOLA MENDOZA: But what?

00:16:32.367 --> 00:16:34.320
ROLAND MARTIN: But even
that idea was a lie.

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:35.611
PAOLA MENDOZA: It wasn't, yeah.

00:16:35.611 --> 00:16:39.490
ROLAND MARTIN: Because if you
are not a white male landowner,

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:40.990
the country was not
founded for you.

00:16:40.990 --> 00:16:42.940
EDDIE HUANG: That's why I
say it's an idea, not a fact.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:43.420
You know what I mean?

00:16:43.420 --> 00:16:45.590
It's been sold around
the world as this idea.

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:45.720
LUVVIE AJAYI: Right.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:47.440
EDDIE HUANG: But that's
our cultural soft powers

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:48.690
that we've exported this idea.

00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:51.729
VINT CERF: Actually, it's
an aspiration and which

00:16:51.729 --> 00:16:52.270
it involved--

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:53.090
EDDIE HUANG: It's a lifestyle.

00:16:53.090 --> 00:16:54.040
LUVVIE AJAYI: I
don't even think--

00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:55.081
that's the thing, though.

00:16:55.081 --> 00:16:57.610
I don't even think America
aspires for equality.

00:16:57.610 --> 00:16:58.510
That's the thing.

00:16:58.510 --> 00:17:03.150
This country plays the
global captain save a planet,

00:17:03.150 --> 00:17:06.069
like runs through and be like
there's no democracy here.

00:17:06.069 --> 00:17:07.390
We're going to bomb your place.

00:17:07.390 --> 00:17:11.140
Meanwhile, in our own country,
what happens, I think America--

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:13.730
back to one of your points--

00:17:13.730 --> 00:17:16.030
one of the reasons why
we can't move forward

00:17:16.030 --> 00:17:18.624
is because America
does not do a good job

00:17:18.624 --> 00:17:21.040
of looking at itself in the
mirror and being like, oh, OK.

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:22.900
I see what's coming back at me.

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:26.579
It's playing this global leader
has this very high moral stance

00:17:26.579 --> 00:17:27.079
elsewhere.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:28.810
But what's happening
in the country

00:17:28.810 --> 00:17:30.970
is just not-- it's the
same things we're bombing

00:17:30.970 --> 00:17:32.260
people for is happening here.

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:32.610
ROLAND MARTIN:
Well, you're right.

00:17:32.610 --> 00:17:35.237
I think if you read Stephen
Kinzer's book, "Overthrow,"

00:17:35.237 --> 00:17:36.820
if you want to look
at what Russia did

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:37.920
to us in the last election--

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:38.215
PAOLA MENDOZA: Right.

00:17:38.215 --> 00:17:38.510
You've done.

00:17:38.510 --> 00:17:40.301
ROLAND MARTIN: Hell,
we did that going back

00:17:40.301 --> 00:17:42.421
to [INAUDIBLE] in Iran in 1954.

00:17:42.421 --> 00:17:44.420
PAOLA MENDOZA: We did
that to all Latin America.

00:17:44.420 --> 00:17:47.590
ROLAND MARTIN: We pretty
perfected the art of jacking up

00:17:47.590 --> 00:17:48.280
a country--

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:48.680
PAOLA MENDOZA: Yes.

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:50.051
ROLAND MARTIN:
--with that group.

00:17:50.051 --> 00:17:50.510
No, seriously.

00:17:50.510 --> 00:17:50.870
PAOLA MENDOZA: Fact.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:51.370
It's true.

00:17:51.370 --> 00:17:52.076
Fact.

00:17:52.076 --> 00:17:54.700
ROLAND MARTIN: But the reason I
want to stay on this whole idea

00:17:54.700 --> 00:17:57.430
in terms of this
ideal, because as we're

00:17:57.430 --> 00:18:00.370
talking about moving
discussions forward, trying

00:18:00.370 --> 00:18:03.100
to figure it out, I think
we have to deal with that.

00:18:03.100 --> 00:18:05.580
Because if you look
at income inequality

00:18:05.580 --> 00:18:07.880
now, if you look
at how much wealth

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:10.570
is being held in
so few hands, it

00:18:10.570 --> 00:18:13.490
is literally a 21st
century version

00:18:13.490 --> 00:18:15.257
of when this
country was created.

00:18:15.257 --> 00:18:16.090
PAOLA MENDOZA: Yeah.

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:16.990
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:19.615
ROLAND MARTIN: You're literally
in the exact same spot in terms

00:18:19.615 --> 00:18:21.740
of a handful of
people with wealth

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:25.440
determining the future
direction of the country.

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:28.100
And so I go back to
this notion of resist.

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:32.087
We are resisting to do what?

00:18:32.087 --> 00:18:33.170
VINT CERF: Well, presume--

00:18:33.170 --> 00:18:34.790
ROLAND MARTIN: To get what?

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:38.300
VINT CERF: Presumably more
equal treatment for everyone.

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:40.350
More equal opportunity
for everyone.

00:18:40.350 --> 00:18:41.183
PAOLA MENDOZA: Yeah.

00:18:41.183 --> 00:18:43.590
I think we're resisting
for two things.

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.380
In this immediate
moment, we're resisting

00:18:45.380 --> 00:18:48.080
to protect our communities,
and all of our communities

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:49.786
are under attack
in various forms.

00:18:49.786 --> 00:18:51.160
And then I would
also say that we

00:18:51.160 --> 00:18:53.630
are resisting for freedom,
like we're resisting

00:18:53.630 --> 00:18:56.660
for freedom of everything.

00:18:56.660 --> 00:18:59.210
And it's something
to strive for.

00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:00.470
Will we get there?

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:02.030
Not in my lifetime.

00:19:02.030 --> 00:19:02.670
I don't know when
we'll get there.

00:19:02.670 --> 00:19:03.120
LUVVIE AJAYI: [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:03.120 --> 00:19:04.328
PAOLA MENDOZA: I know, right?

00:19:04.328 --> 00:19:07.190
Sorry to break it to you.

00:19:07.190 --> 00:19:08.720
EDDIE HUANG: I
think it's the two

00:19:08.720 --> 00:19:12.710
things is that equal protection
of the laws that has never

00:19:12.710 --> 00:19:13.880
been present.

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:16.640
And then the equal opportunity,
because I don't think anybody

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:18.980
here or listening or on
the stage wants anything

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:20.030
given to them.

00:19:20.030 --> 00:19:21.590
I just want the
same opportunity.

00:19:21.590 --> 00:19:23.120
ROLAND MARTIN: Like James
Brown said, open the door.

00:19:23.120 --> 00:19:23.510
I'll get it myself.

00:19:23.510 --> 00:19:23.780
LUVVIE AJAYI: You know--

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:24.738
PAOLA MENDOZA: Exactly.

00:19:24.738 --> 00:19:27.890
LUVVIE AJAYI: You know, I would
want something given to me.

00:19:27.890 --> 00:19:28.670
Yes.

00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:32.335
Because this country
has been people of color

00:19:32.335 --> 00:19:33.710
who have been
doing all the work.

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:35.360
So things have been
given to white people.

00:19:35.360 --> 00:19:37.250
It's time for us to be
given some things too.

00:19:37.250 --> 00:19:38.460
And I think the lack of--

00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:41.660
the guilt that comes with us, we
work so hard that sometimes we

00:19:41.660 --> 00:19:44.260
do get something given to us,
we're like did I deserve it?

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:45.230
Yes.

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:47.450
They've been getting this
for free for 400 years.

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:50.310
It's time for us to get some
things for free too and not

00:19:50.310 --> 00:19:51.400
feel the guilt.

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:53.830
ROLAND MARTIN: I'll
go back to equality

00:19:53.830 --> 00:19:56.000
and equal-- equal
protection, equal protection

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.830
clause, equality.

00:19:57.830 --> 00:19:59.690
A lot of people love
Dr. King and one

00:19:59.690 --> 00:20:02.270
of the things they don't realize
is that he rarely ever used

00:20:02.270 --> 00:20:03.180
the word equality.

00:20:03.180 --> 00:20:04.430
VINT CERF: That's interesting.

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:07.490
ROLAND MARTIN: He
typically said freedom.

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:09.260
He wanted freedom.

00:20:09.260 --> 00:20:13.506
You said that earlier and that
is the moment a child is born,

00:20:13.506 --> 00:20:15.380
even before that, you
want the mother to have

00:20:15.380 --> 00:20:16.670
the same prenatal
care as somebody else.

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:16.935
PAOLA MENDOZA: Yeah.

00:20:16.935 --> 00:20:17.200
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:19.100
ROLAND MARTIN: But you
want freedom, freedom

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:21.840
to drive down the street
and not get pulled over,

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:26.440
freedom to not have somebody
call ICE because you

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:28.220
look Latino and they
think you're also

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:29.690
an illegal immigrant.

00:20:29.690 --> 00:20:32.690
That to me, I , think,
as we're moving forward,

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:34.880
I look at word usage.

00:20:34.880 --> 00:20:38.090
I think that's a more
powerful word, because when

00:20:38.090 --> 00:20:42.350
you hear the so-called patriots,
oh, the founding fathers, they

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:43.645
believed in freedom.

00:20:43.645 --> 00:20:45.050
See, I don't want equality.

00:20:45.050 --> 00:20:46.924
Equality means you've
got to pass another law

00:20:46.924 --> 00:20:47.890
to give it to me.

00:20:47.890 --> 00:20:48.390
No.

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:50.750
I want what you've
got without a law.

00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:51.552
That's freedom.

00:20:51.552 --> 00:20:53.510
VINT CERF: So could I
make a suggestion to you?

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:55.154
When we look at
the Constitution,

00:20:55.154 --> 00:20:56.570
and we look at the
Bill of Rights,

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:59.180
and you see the First Amendment
that speaks about freedom

00:20:59.180 --> 00:21:00.890
of expression,
freedom to assemble,

00:21:00.890 --> 00:21:01.610
freedom of [INAUDIBLE]--

00:21:01.610 --> 00:21:02.810
ROLAND MARTIN: Not equality
of expression, freedom.

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:03.030
VINT CERF: No, no.

00:21:03.030 --> 00:21:03.530
Yes.

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:04.820
I agree with you.

00:21:04.820 --> 00:21:06.320
But I wanted to
emphasize something

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:07.700
that you didn't mention.

00:21:07.700 --> 00:21:09.200
And that's another
notion of freedom

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:12.680
from harm, which is not
in our Bill of Rights

00:21:12.680 --> 00:21:14.000
but it should be.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:17.310
That's the one thing that
we are willing to give up

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:22.010
a certain amount of freedom
in exchange for safety.

00:21:22.010 --> 00:21:24.090
And that's part of
the social contract.

00:21:24.090 --> 00:21:26.720
It's a very tricky
concept, but it's one

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:29.420
that we have to embrace
because without that--

00:21:29.420 --> 00:21:34.790
in theory, my freedom of
action should stop about 1 cm

00:21:34.790 --> 00:21:36.414
from your nose.

00:21:36.414 --> 00:21:38.622
ROLAND MARTIN: Actually it
should stop in that chair.

00:21:38.622 --> 00:21:41.077
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:41.077 --> 00:21:44.514
That's where it should stop.

00:21:44.514 --> 00:21:48.210
You get your ass out that chair,
it's going to be a problem.

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:50.400
EDDIE HUANG: That's actually
the more conservative

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:51.660
interpretation of Locke.

00:21:51.660 --> 00:21:54.230
He has the more liberal
interpretation of Locke

00:21:54.230 --> 00:21:56.250
in the social contract,
which is that it's

00:21:56.250 --> 00:21:58.175
up to the centimeter
of your nose.

00:21:58.175 --> 00:22:00.960
It's that you can express
your freedom to the extent

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:03.360
that it does not impose
on someone else's

00:22:03.360 --> 00:22:05.570
unlimited freedom.

00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:07.680
And so I think as a
society it's like boxing.

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:09.650
It's about mastering
your distance.

00:22:09.650 --> 00:22:11.233
ROLAND MARTIN: So
I'll throw this out.

00:22:11.233 --> 00:22:14.370
So here we have
massive changes when

00:22:14.370 --> 00:22:16.430
I look at what young
folks are doing today,

00:22:16.430 --> 00:22:20.430
which is not unlike any
other areas of history.

00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:21.990
I can think back to SNCC--

00:22:21.990 --> 00:22:23.880
Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee--

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:26.254
1960s, meeting at Shaw
University and what they did

00:22:26.254 --> 00:22:28.170
and how they drove the
Black Freedom Movement.

00:22:28.170 --> 00:22:28.957
VINT CERF: SDS.

00:22:28.957 --> 00:22:31.290
ROLAND MARTIN: But here's
what's very interesting to me,

00:22:31.290 --> 00:22:34.200
is that when you begin to look
at polling data, when you look

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:36.780
at white millennials
who believe today

00:22:36.780 --> 00:22:41.732
that racism against whites is
just as significant as it is

00:22:41.732 --> 00:22:43.440
against African-Americans--
to your point

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:46.320
about it being a construct--
we have, I believe,

00:22:46.320 --> 00:22:49.260
sold ourselves this
false notion that, oh,

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:51.210
but kids they all
listen to hip hop.

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:51.960
It's all good.

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:55.908
LUVVIE AJAYI: It's the
least racist generation.

00:22:55.908 --> 00:22:58.033
ROLAND MARTIN: You find
that hilarious, I can tell.

00:22:58.033 --> 00:23:00.690
EDDIE HUANG: I find it hilarious
because I remember growing up,

00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:04.900
I actually felt a
lot of solidarity.

00:23:04.900 --> 00:23:08.610
I found a lot of connectivity
to hip hop music.

00:23:08.610 --> 00:23:12.010
It was the music that made me
feel less alone and less alien

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:14.940
because I was the only
Chinese kid in school.

00:23:14.940 --> 00:23:18.450
But I knew that a
lot of the other kids

00:23:18.450 --> 00:23:20.830
listening to it, that
it was a phase for them.

00:23:20.830 --> 00:23:22.880
It was a costume, like
they come back from summer

00:23:22.880 --> 00:23:25.976
and it's like, oh, I'm wearing
FUBU and Phat Farm now,

00:23:25.976 --> 00:23:28.350
but then I knew next summer
they'd be wearing Abercrombie

00:23:28.350 --> 00:23:29.541
&amp; Fitch, you know?

00:23:29.541 --> 00:23:30.332
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:23:30.332 --> 00:23:32.650
EDDIE HUANG: And by the
time people went to college,

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:33.690
they just dropped it.

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:34.814
A lot of people dropped it.

00:23:34.814 --> 00:23:37.840
But then hip hop became
a mainstream culture.

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:43.050
But I think that says
more about this art form

00:23:43.050 --> 00:23:45.450
that black communities
created, the power of hip hop

00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:46.782
and how undeniable it is.

00:23:46.782 --> 00:23:48.990
It's the most powerful
movement of the last 30 years.

00:23:48.990 --> 00:23:50.531
ROLAND MARTIN: What
I'm trying to say

00:23:50.531 --> 00:23:53.130
is that we can't
live on this idea

00:23:53.130 --> 00:23:58.710
that just because there are
folks today who are 24, 25, 26,

00:23:58.710 --> 00:24:01.920
that somehow everything
is going to change

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:04.590
because they live in a
much more diverse world

00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:06.090
than their parents.

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:09.150
We actually still
take on the identity

00:24:09.150 --> 00:24:10.500
and the views of our parents.

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:11.000
How--

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:12.210
EDDIE HUANG: It
becomes more insidious

00:24:12.210 --> 00:24:13.920
when you don't think
there is an actual threat.

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:14.430
PAOLA MENDOZA: Right.

00:24:14.430 --> 00:24:15.221
EDDIE HUANG: Right?

00:24:15.221 --> 00:24:19.170
And so I think the ABC show,
that "Fresh Off The Boat"

00:24:19.170 --> 00:24:22.620
is a real good example of
they'll use your yellow faces

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:24.240
and tell white stories.

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:25.810
You know?

00:24:25.810 --> 00:24:27.360
ROLAND MARTIN: So
moving forward,

00:24:27.360 --> 00:24:30.030
how do we be mindful
of that to ensure

00:24:30.030 --> 00:24:32.330
we don't fall into the
trap of just assuming,

00:24:32.330 --> 00:24:33.600
oh, it's all good?

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:36.330
EDDIE HUANG: I'm probably
the wrong person to ask.

00:24:36.330 --> 00:24:38.320
LUVVIE AJAYI: Well,
we shouldn't assume.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:39.960
So part of the
thing is we always

00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:43.080
assume people are at the same
place we are in understanding,

00:24:43.080 --> 00:24:45.330
in knowledge and
wherever our beliefs are.

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:46.560
And that's completely wrong.

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:48.540
Everyone got shocked
November 9 being

00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:50.767
like, oh god, I thought
everybody I knew

00:24:50.767 --> 00:24:51.600
was voting this way.

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:52.134
No.

00:24:52.134 --> 00:24:53.550
That assumption
is wrong, which is

00:24:53.550 --> 00:24:55.424
why the conversation
needs to happen in rooms

00:24:55.424 --> 00:24:57.557
that are difficult or not.

00:24:57.557 --> 00:24:59.640
We need to talk about white
privilege and the fact

00:24:59.640 --> 00:25:01.470
that most people don't even
know what white privilege means.

00:25:01.470 --> 00:25:03.220
They just think it
means that I got things

00:25:03.220 --> 00:25:04.620
handed to me all my life.

00:25:04.620 --> 00:25:08.789
These kids who are 24, 25
still doing blackface parties.

00:25:08.789 --> 00:25:10.580
And then we want to
sit and be like they're

00:25:10.580 --> 00:25:11.820
the least racist generation.

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:12.960
No, they're not.

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:14.850
They're being raised
by racists, so they're

00:25:14.850 --> 00:25:16.390
going to be racist too.

00:25:16.390 --> 00:25:19.200
It doesn't matter if they're
around black people all day.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:21.720
If their mom and your dad
has beaten in your head

00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:24.630
that this is exactly how--
white supremacy and the idea

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:26.490
of genetic supremacy.

00:25:26.490 --> 00:25:28.590
And that is going to be
what they carry with them.

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:30.570
So we have to bring it to them.

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:36.060
ROLAND MARTIN: Does it
behoove us to quickly call

00:25:36.060 --> 00:25:38.890
someone or something racist?

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:41.702
Here's is why I'm putting that
out there-- before you answer--

00:25:41.702 --> 00:25:42.660
so here's what happens.

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:44.940
We have these
conversations today.

00:25:44.940 --> 00:25:47.970
An event happens,
let's say blackface.

00:25:47.970 --> 00:25:50.970
All of a sudden it
goes, that's racist.

00:25:50.970 --> 00:25:52.350
No, it's not.

00:25:52.350 --> 00:25:55.680
The conversation then is
no longer about blackface.

00:25:55.680 --> 00:25:58.610
The conversation is now you're
racist, you're not a racist.

00:25:58.610 --> 00:25:59.340
EDDIE HUANG: Yeah,
self-preservation.

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:00.756
ROLAND MARTIN: The
argument that I

00:26:00.756 --> 00:26:04.470
make is there is a whole lot
of stuff in between racist

00:26:04.470 --> 00:26:05.550
and non-racist.

00:26:05.550 --> 00:26:07.770
I've rarely called
someone a racist,

00:26:07.770 --> 00:26:11.940
because I want to stay focused
on exactly what happened

00:26:11.940 --> 00:26:16.050
as opposed to that conversation,
because it will quickly shift.

00:26:16.050 --> 00:26:16.800
EDDIE HUANG: Yeah.

00:26:16.800 --> 00:26:19.110
For me, if I'm talking
to somebody about race

00:26:19.110 --> 00:26:21.330
or I feel like maybe
something is racist,

00:26:21.330 --> 00:26:24.030
I try to establish with
them in the conversation,

00:26:24.030 --> 00:26:27.400
I don't want anything from you.

00:26:27.400 --> 00:26:28.234
I want this for you.

00:26:28.234 --> 00:26:29.233
Do you know what I mean?

00:26:29.233 --> 00:26:31.170
I want you to have
this understanding

00:26:31.170 --> 00:26:34.300
so everything I'm telling you
is not for me to report you

00:26:34.300 --> 00:26:36.490
or to complain about
you or ruin your career.

00:26:36.490 --> 00:26:38.925
I'm here for you to get
closer to the truth.

00:26:38.925 --> 00:26:39.800
You know what I mean?

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:40.610
ROLAND MARTIN: Paola,
I'm going to go to you.

00:26:40.610 --> 00:26:42.318
So for instance, same
thing happened when

00:26:42.318 --> 00:26:43.780
it came to the Women's March.

00:26:43.780 --> 00:26:46.060
I've been highly critical of the
National Organization for Women

00:26:46.060 --> 00:26:48.393
for a long time because it
should have been the National

00:26:48.393 --> 00:26:49.680
Organization for White Women.

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:50.410
PAOLA MENDOZA: Agreed.

00:26:50.410 --> 00:26:52.618
ROLAND MARTIN: So when a
14-year-old girl in McKinney

00:26:52.618 --> 00:26:55.670
had her face slammed into
the ground, now said nothing.

00:26:55.670 --> 00:26:58.300
And I put them on blast and
ever since then, every time

00:26:58.300 --> 00:26:59.800
something happens
with a black girl,

00:26:59.800 --> 00:27:02.470
they put that statement
out in about 20 minutes.

00:27:02.470 --> 00:27:06.340
But the point being, if you
say it now you're racist,

00:27:06.340 --> 00:27:08.830
the reaction from these
white liberal women,

00:27:08.830 --> 00:27:10.430
oh my god, I'm not racist?

00:27:10.430 --> 00:27:12.177
No, but you're silent.

00:27:12.177 --> 00:27:12.760
MENDOZA: Yeah.

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:15.280
So this is exactly what I
was going to talk about,

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:18.070
is the idea and the power of
language or lack of language.

00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:20.800
So I work in the immigration
space, specifically

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:23.500
in the undocumented space,
and this is a new territory

00:27:23.500 --> 00:27:25.030
for most people.

00:27:25.030 --> 00:27:27.040
So people don't necessarily
know the language.

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:29.170
So you will hear
people say "illegal"

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:30.520
as opposed to "undocumented."

00:27:30.520 --> 00:27:32.770
And I've kind of
perfected the way

00:27:32.770 --> 00:27:37.210
in which to correct someone in a
non-confrontational, productive

00:27:37.210 --> 00:27:39.790
way so that they actually
understand why they shouldn't

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:40.550
use that language.

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:42.760
I don't call people out
publicly, or if I do,

00:27:42.760 --> 00:27:45.910
it's a very safe space
in which to do it in.

00:27:45.910 --> 00:27:47.669
And I think that goes
to your question,

00:27:47.669 --> 00:27:49.210
because at the end
of the day, what's

00:27:49.210 --> 00:27:52.360
important to me in that
circumstance in particular

00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:56.140
is to educate, empower,
and create a conversation.

00:27:56.140 --> 00:27:58.210
And when we are attacking
people right away,

00:27:58.210 --> 00:28:01.300
then that ability to have a
conversation is unattainable.

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:04.210
But also keeping in mind that
there are just some people

00:28:04.210 --> 00:28:06.080
that I will not engage
in conversation with,

00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:08.290
and those are just
the outliers that we

00:28:08.290 --> 00:28:10.840
don't talk to or engage with.

00:28:10.840 --> 00:28:12.940
And with regards to
the Women's March,

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:14.440
I think one of the
things that we're

00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:18.970
most proud of is that we were
able to push the needle forward

00:28:18.970 --> 00:28:21.850
within the women's
movement to talk

00:28:21.850 --> 00:28:26.410
about this idea of feminism
being for white women

00:28:26.410 --> 00:28:28.750
and really having white
women in particular

00:28:28.750 --> 00:28:33.780
understand why feminism had
become so selectively white.

00:28:33.780 --> 00:28:36.880
And within the organization,
we had numerous conversations

00:28:36.880 --> 00:28:38.930
where we were crying,
upset, laughing.

00:28:38.930 --> 00:28:40.150
And these were strangers.

00:28:40.150 --> 00:28:41.890
These were 25
women, 30 women that

00:28:41.890 --> 00:28:44.110
came together, didn't
really know one another,

00:28:44.110 --> 00:28:45.430
to have these discussions.

00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:49.180
And the people that were really
having the most emotionally

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:51.160
difficult discussions
were the white women

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:53.285
because they were being
confronted in a space where

00:28:53.285 --> 00:28:56.279
they were actually equal
in numbers of women

00:28:56.279 --> 00:28:57.320
of color and white women.

00:28:57.320 --> 00:28:58.520
They were not the majority.

00:28:58.520 --> 00:28:59.890
And so I always--

00:28:59.890 --> 00:29:01.260
ROLAND MARTIN: And they
thought everything was good.

00:29:01.260 --> 00:29:01.630
PAOLA MENDOZA: Oh, yeah.

00:29:01.630 --> 00:29:02.260
They did know.

00:29:02.260 --> 00:29:03.190
They honestly didn't know.

00:29:03.190 --> 00:29:05.020
And so you don't know
what you don't know.

00:29:05.020 --> 00:29:07.360
So that's where you
start the conversation.

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:10.570
And it's exhausting and tiring
and emotionally draining,

00:29:10.570 --> 00:29:14.320
but it's one conversation
that each individual can

00:29:14.320 --> 00:29:15.430
choose to take on.

00:29:15.430 --> 00:29:17.890
So my point is that
again, it goes back

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:22.660
to this idea of conversations,
of how do you call someone

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:24.430
out in a way that's
productive and where

00:29:24.430 --> 00:29:25.000
they don't get defensive.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:25.917
LUVVIE AJAYI: Call in.

00:29:25.917 --> 00:29:26.875
PAOLA MENDOZA: Exactly.

00:29:26.875 --> 00:29:27.600
You call them in.

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:29.058
ROLAND MARTIN: Let
me do this here.

00:29:29.058 --> 00:29:33.040
So how many folks in the
room have heard of Title IX?

00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:35.020
VINT CERF: Oh yeah.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:36.640
ROLAND MARTIN: How
many of you believe

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:39.237
that Title IX was about sports?

00:29:39.237 --> 00:29:39.820
VINT CERF: No.

00:29:39.820 --> 00:29:40.854
It was about gender.

00:29:40.854 --> 00:29:41.770
ROLAND MARTIN: No, no.

00:29:41.770 --> 00:29:45.880
It was about-- the way that
it's been positioned that it's

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:48.280
about sports and gender.

00:29:48.280 --> 00:29:51.190
But if you actually
go back, Title IX

00:29:51.190 --> 00:29:53.230
was created to
specifically open up

00:29:53.230 --> 00:29:56.920
the professional schools
for women, doctors, lawyers,

00:29:56.920 --> 00:29:57.580
dentists.

00:29:57.580 --> 00:29:59.110
Now let me ask this question.

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:04.730
Who knows where Title
IX even comes from?

00:30:04.730 --> 00:30:05.990
Precisely.

00:30:05.990 --> 00:30:08.941
The 1964 Civil Rights Act.

00:30:08.941 --> 00:30:12.470
So Title IX gets passed, '72.

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:13.390
Gets passed.

00:30:13.390 --> 00:30:16.430
You see an explosion of women
become doctors, dentists,

00:30:16.430 --> 00:30:19.280
lawyers, engineers, in
professional schools.

00:30:19.280 --> 00:30:21.950
Largely white women, because
still the opportunities

00:30:21.950 --> 00:30:23.700
were being closed
for black women.

00:30:23.700 --> 00:30:25.331
So all these women--

00:30:25.331 --> 00:30:27.080
talking about a lot
of women in the room--

00:30:27.080 --> 00:30:28.580
who then go into
corporate America,

00:30:28.580 --> 00:30:31.190
who get all these
particular jobs.

00:30:31.190 --> 00:30:32.090
Guess what?

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:35.090
They were able to advance
because black folks marched

00:30:35.090 --> 00:30:36.740
to get the '64 Civil
Rights Act passed.

00:30:36.740 --> 00:30:37.769
PAOLA MENDOZA: Exactly.

00:30:37.769 --> 00:30:39.560
ROLAND MARTIN: Now when
you throw that out,

00:30:39.560 --> 00:30:41.780
and I've done this in speeches,
white women in the room

00:30:41.780 --> 00:30:43.155
look at me like,
oh, my god, what

00:30:43.155 --> 00:30:44.970
the hell is he talking about?

00:30:44.970 --> 00:30:47.330
To Eddie's point, you're
talking about if you

00:30:47.330 --> 00:30:49.610
are Chinese or
Korean or Japanese

00:30:49.610 --> 00:30:53.210
and you appreciate voting
with your native tongue

00:30:53.210 --> 00:30:55.000
in the ballot,
thank black people

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:56.945
and the 1965 Voting Rights Act.

00:30:56.945 --> 00:30:59.570
I go back to the reconstruction
amendment, the Equal Protection

00:30:59.570 --> 00:31:02.030
Clause, 14th Amendment,
that came out after slavery.

00:31:02.030 --> 00:31:03.170
The point I'm making is--

00:31:03.170 --> 00:31:04.580
also if you're disabled.

00:31:04.580 --> 00:31:05.990
Remember the disabilities act?

00:31:05.990 --> 00:31:07.880
Provision of the '64
Civil Rights Act.

00:31:07.880 --> 00:31:11.390
All of these laws
that have been changed

00:31:11.390 --> 00:31:14.320
were a result of the
black freedom movement.

00:31:14.320 --> 00:31:15.770
And when you throw
that out there,

00:31:15.770 --> 00:31:17.932
people then go, oh,
where you going?

00:31:17.932 --> 00:31:19.640
Which allows me to go
into the next part.

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:22.610
That is when you look at
Black Lives Matter and then

00:31:22.610 --> 00:31:24.740
these efforts that
are happening today,

00:31:24.740 --> 00:31:27.560
these laws that are being--
these changes are being forced

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:30.960
not to just benefit black folks,
but again, like everything else

00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:35.330
that I just said, to benefit
every other American.

00:31:35.330 --> 00:31:38.020
How do we get that
through folks' heads

00:31:38.020 --> 00:31:40.940
that it just ain't
a black thing?

00:31:40.940 --> 00:31:43.180
A body camera can
save your ass, too.

00:31:46.760 --> 00:31:48.020
VINT CERF: Good point.

00:31:48.020 --> 00:31:52.270
EDDIE HUANG: As a kid, like, I
didn't see Asian politicians.

00:31:52.270 --> 00:31:54.320
I didn't see that
many Asian leaders.

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:56.540
There was not any
representation of us

00:31:56.540 --> 00:31:58.760
culturally besides Bruce Lee.

00:31:58.760 --> 00:31:59.930
You know?

00:31:59.930 --> 00:32:02.990
And I read Hank
Aaron's autobiography.

00:32:02.990 --> 00:32:05.040
I would read "Thank
You, Jackie Robinson."

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:06.500
I listened to Charles Barkley.

00:32:06.500 --> 00:32:08.916
You know, like, as much he
didn't want to be a role model,

00:32:08.916 --> 00:32:10.340
he was my role model, you know?

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:11.630
And I read about the march.

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:13.880
I read about Malcolm
X, Martin Luther King.

00:32:13.880 --> 00:32:17.840
And I read, "I Have A Dream"
and compared it to "Letter

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:18.767
From Birmingham Jail."

00:32:18.767 --> 00:32:19.850
And I started to realize--

00:32:19.850 --> 00:32:23.000
I was like, black people
have paved the way for anyone

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:25.190
of difference in America.

00:32:25.190 --> 00:32:29.660
And I think for me, I grew up
just always wanting solidarity,

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:31.970
because I could see
strength in solidarity

00:32:31.970 --> 00:32:33.470
and I could see how
I was benefiting

00:32:33.470 --> 00:32:35.870
from the work of
black Americans.

00:32:35.870 --> 00:32:38.517
And going to the Women's March--

00:32:38.517 --> 00:32:40.100
you know, I went to
the Women's March.

00:32:40.100 --> 00:32:42.224
It was one of the most
incredible things I've seen.

00:32:42.224 --> 00:32:45.040
And once I saw Trump
going at women,

00:32:45.040 --> 00:32:47.540
I was like, we're actually going
to make some progress here,

00:32:47.540 --> 00:32:49.430
because everybody has a mother.

00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:53.220
Everybody has been kind of
slandered by this man now.

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:55.300
And this is now
everybody's fight

00:32:55.300 --> 00:32:55.610
and everybody has to join in.

00:32:55.610 --> 00:32:56.482
ROLAND MARTIN: Yes.

00:32:56.482 --> 00:32:57.440
EDDIE HUANG: And then--

00:32:57.440 --> 00:32:57.940
I'm sorry.

00:32:57.940 --> 00:32:59.390
I haven't finished the point.

00:32:59.390 --> 00:33:04.070
Then the Women's March became
this platform and this canvas

00:33:04.070 --> 00:33:07.670
that everyone could bring their
issues and their stories to.

00:33:07.670 --> 00:33:10.100
And I saw tons of
Black Lives posters.

00:33:10.100 --> 00:33:12.890
And you know, it
was a place where

00:33:12.890 --> 00:33:15.020
everyone had a place
to come have a voice

00:33:15.020 --> 00:33:16.370
and stand up for something.

00:33:16.370 --> 00:33:18.140
And the women at
the march really, I

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:19.640
think, carried the
torch and carried

00:33:19.640 --> 00:33:23.150
a lot of people's issues
for them that day.

00:33:23.150 --> 00:33:25.800
ROLAND MARTIN: Yet 53% of
white women voted for Trump.

00:33:25.800 --> 00:33:30.050
Yet people then, after
the election, said whoa,

00:33:30.050 --> 00:33:33.919
I was voting for this,
I totally ignored this.

00:33:33.919 --> 00:33:35.960
Like all the people right
now who are now crying,

00:33:35.960 --> 00:33:37.850
please don't take
my health care.

00:33:37.850 --> 00:33:39.500
Now you're trying to wake up.

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:42.200
So as we're moving forward, all
these different movements that

00:33:42.200 --> 00:33:42.830
are going on--

00:33:42.830 --> 00:33:43.610
EDDIE HUANG: I'll
take them whenever

00:33:43.610 --> 00:33:44.818
they want to wake up, though.

00:33:44.818 --> 00:33:45.775
You know what I mean?

00:33:45.775 --> 00:33:47.525
LUVVIE AJAYI: I sat
out the Women's March,

00:33:47.525 --> 00:33:50.330
and it was a persons
decision to do that.

00:33:50.330 --> 00:33:52.190
Because I was like,
you know what?

00:33:52.190 --> 00:33:54.230
Yes, black people are
always showing up.

00:33:54.230 --> 00:33:57.094
Honestly, on this
day, I don't want to.

00:33:57.094 --> 00:33:58.760
So I actually sat
home, and I didn't go.

00:33:58.760 --> 00:34:01.080
But I was like, props
to everybody who went,

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:03.830
and I really respected the
significance of the event

00:34:03.830 --> 00:34:05.300
and how massive it was.

00:34:05.300 --> 00:34:08.000
I mean, biggest protest ever.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:10.969
OK, so that was epic.

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:15.050
But the fatigue that comes
from always showing up

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:17.600
for people who never show
up for you, on that day,

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:20.469
I was not feeling the need
to be uniting with anybody.

00:34:20.469 --> 00:34:22.940
I was like, I
[INAUDIBLE] afterwards.

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:25.340
But today, what happens
when black women do

00:34:25.340 --> 00:34:28.219
decide to all sit out one day?

00:34:28.219 --> 00:34:29.389
If we don't show up.

00:34:29.389 --> 00:34:31.639
Like, how far would we be--

00:34:31.639 --> 00:34:33.080
how far would women be?

00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:35.655
Even though we usually get
the brunt of, oh, my god,

00:34:35.655 --> 00:34:37.530
the Black Lives Matter
people are protesting.

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:40.389
They should like,
stop stopping traffic.

00:34:40.389 --> 00:34:41.989
Meanwhile not
realizing that, like,

00:34:41.989 --> 00:34:43.572
your kids are
benefiting from the fact

00:34:43.572 --> 00:34:45.320
that these people
are stopping traffic.

00:34:45.320 --> 00:34:47.000
So I mean, I think it's
really important for people

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:48.080
to acknowledge that.

00:34:48.080 --> 00:34:50.000
It's the fact that
black Americans do not

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:53.570
get enough credit for the amount
of work that they've put on--

00:34:53.570 --> 00:34:55.190
I was born in
Nigeria, so I'm also

00:34:55.190 --> 00:34:58.220
an immigrant in that I didn't
come here until I was nine.

00:34:58.220 --> 00:35:03.180
And Africans come here
and get really successful,

00:35:03.180 --> 00:35:05.180
but we also have to
acknowledge the reason we're

00:35:05.180 --> 00:35:07.700
able to do that is
because when we come here,

00:35:07.700 --> 00:35:10.180
all the work that black
Americans have done

00:35:10.180 --> 00:35:12.470
allow us to come here and
then become doctors in three

00:35:12.470 --> 00:35:15.350
years and four years, and
then be able to be, like,

00:35:15.350 --> 00:35:18.697
in the 10%, which is amazing.

00:35:18.697 --> 00:35:20.780
So I just wanted to take
this moment to say, like,

00:35:20.780 --> 00:35:23.290
black Americans, y'all
are super heroes.

00:35:23.290 --> 00:35:24.860
You don't get told that enough.

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:27.884
And history doesn't give you
enough credit, but it should.

00:35:27.884 --> 00:35:29.300
PAOLA MENDOZA: And
to that point--

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:32.720
and this is something that I'd
like to say publicly as often

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:33.830
as I can--

00:35:33.830 --> 00:35:36.590
that the Women's March
was as successful

00:35:36.590 --> 00:35:39.800
as it was because we were
literally on the backs of Black

00:35:39.800 --> 00:35:40.490
Lives Matter.

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:43.100
Black Lives Matter had been
training the American people

00:35:43.100 --> 00:35:45.560
for two, three years previous
to the women's movement

00:35:45.560 --> 00:35:49.070
to go out to the streets, to
protest, to shut things down.

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:52.370
And it was when
the perfect event

00:35:52.370 --> 00:35:55.430
of Donald Trump and
everything that he

00:35:55.430 --> 00:35:59.000
had done to women and an
event was posted on Facebook

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:02.060
that we had just the
perfect energy, synergy,

00:36:02.060 --> 00:36:04.700
whatever you want to call
it, to get millions of people

00:36:04.700 --> 00:36:05.840
out to the street.

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:08.780
But I don't think that we would
have had that had Black Lives

00:36:08.780 --> 00:36:11.450
Matter not been happening for
three years previous to that.

00:36:11.450 --> 00:36:13.040
And also what you're
talking about I

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:14.706
think at the end of
the day is something

00:36:14.706 --> 00:36:16.710
that is organizing 101.

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:19.010
When we put the most
marginalized people

00:36:19.010 --> 00:36:22.250
at the center of the movement,
and we work towards them,

00:36:22.250 --> 00:36:26.220
and we realize that our freedom
is bound to their freedom,

00:36:26.220 --> 00:36:27.950
that's the work that
needs to get done.

00:36:27.950 --> 00:36:29.510
So when we're here
in this space,

00:36:29.510 --> 00:36:32.664
and we're talking about race,
the reason race is important

00:36:32.664 --> 00:36:34.580
and the reason why we
need to be uncomfortable

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:37.280
and the reason why we need to
have these daring discussions

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:41.810
is because when we have them, we
will all start to become free.

00:36:41.810 --> 00:36:44.600
We will all get closer to that
place that we're striving for.

00:36:44.600 --> 00:36:48.200
And so I think that's why Google
is having this conversation,

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:49.820
because they are
obviously-- you all

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:52.670
are obviously at the forefront
of where we need to go.

00:36:52.670 --> 00:36:54.120
And that is why
it's important to,

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:56.540
whether if you're white, if
you're black, if you're Latino,

00:36:56.540 --> 00:36:58.320
if you're undocumented, if
you're gay, if you're straight,

00:36:58.320 --> 00:36:59.990
if you're disabled,
whatever it is--

00:36:59.990 --> 00:37:02.420
that is the importance and
the power of the conversation.

00:37:02.420 --> 00:37:05.086
ROLAND MARTIN: So but how are we
dealing with intersectionality?

00:37:05.182 --> 00:37:06.140
EDDIE HUANG: I'm sorry.

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:09.230
I really want to respond to
what she said, because I really

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:10.790
understand your frustration.

00:37:10.790 --> 00:37:13.340
And you don't need
me to say it, but I

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:17.290
think it's very, very fair
that some people sat out

00:37:17.290 --> 00:37:18.290
the Women's March.

00:37:18.290 --> 00:37:20.120
Because it's like the
sword in the stone,

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:21.120
do you know what I mean?

00:37:21.120 --> 00:37:23.450
It's like, you know,
Black Lives Matter

00:37:23.450 --> 00:37:25.400
have been pulling on
this sword in the stone,

00:37:25.400 --> 00:37:27.560
doing all the work
pushing it forward,

00:37:27.560 --> 00:37:29.390
trying to open America's eyes.

00:37:29.390 --> 00:37:31.022
And a lot of people
are just like, why

00:37:31.022 --> 00:37:33.230
are you saying-- why are we
talking about Black Lives

00:37:33.230 --> 00:37:33.860
Matter?

00:37:33.860 --> 00:37:35.690
Treating it almost
like a nuisance,

00:37:35.690 --> 00:37:35.930
do you know what I mean?

00:37:35.930 --> 00:37:37.305
Treating Colin
Kaepernick like he

00:37:37.305 --> 00:37:39.050
was a nuisance, when
in fact that man

00:37:39.050 --> 00:37:43.220
sacrificed his career to make
a statement and awaken America.

00:37:43.220 --> 00:37:46.940
And it has to be frustrating
from a black perspective

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:48.900
to see that when white
women were attacked,

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:52.700
that then the sword was
taken out of the stone.

00:37:52.700 --> 00:37:55.046
ROLAND MARTIN: That's called
being black in America.

00:37:55.046 --> 00:37:57.005
No, I mean, that's the reality.

00:37:57.005 --> 00:37:58.100
EDDIE HUANG: Even a China man
can understand that, though.

00:37:58.100 --> 00:37:59.808
ROLAND MARTIN: We're
just like, you know.

00:37:59.808 --> 00:38:01.940
EDDIE HUANG: I'd like
to say this, too--

00:38:01.940 --> 00:38:03.940
ROLAND MARTIN: You got
the New York Giants owner

00:38:03.940 --> 00:38:06.530
in today's newspaper talking
about we got all these letters

00:38:06.530 --> 00:38:08.946
from Giants fans saying we're
going to boycott if you sign

00:38:08.946 --> 00:38:10.850
Kaepernick, but they
didn't say a damn thing

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:12.125
when they had a
kicker who was beating

00:38:12.125 --> 00:38:12.840
the hell out of his wife.

00:38:12.840 --> 00:38:13.590
EDDIE HUANG: Yeah.

00:38:13.590 --> 00:38:16.670
And the other thing, too, is I
would say, is, like, I totally

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:18.590
get the frustration,
but sometimes I

00:38:18.590 --> 00:38:21.537
feel like, as a minority
or a person of color,

00:38:21.537 --> 00:38:23.870
however everyone's supposed
to be identified these days,

00:38:23.870 --> 00:38:26.000
it's like unfortunately,
we may not have

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:27.440
the privilege of sitting out.

00:38:27.440 --> 00:38:27.650
ROLAND MARTIN: No, no, no.

00:38:27.650 --> 00:38:29.270
EDDIE HUANG: [INAUDIBLE],,
you know what I mean?

00:38:29.270 --> 00:38:31.269
ROLAND MARTIN: Here's how
I see her sitting out.

00:38:31.269 --> 00:38:33.994
It's sort of like if we're
in a tug of war, it's like--

00:38:33.994 --> 00:38:36.160
EDDIE HUANG: You and Rick
Mahorn pull the chair out.

00:38:36.160 --> 00:38:36.930
ROLAND MARTIN: No, it's like--

00:38:36.930 --> 00:38:37.760
I'm going to take a rest.

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:38.180
[INAUDIBLE]

00:38:38.180 --> 00:38:38.340
LUVVIE AJAYI: That's it.

00:38:38.340 --> 00:38:38.840
That's it.

00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:39.589
ROLAND MARTIN: No.

00:38:39.589 --> 00:38:41.292
Basically, we're
like, in a tug of war,

00:38:41.292 --> 00:38:42.500
I'm going to take a breather.

00:38:42.500 --> 00:38:43.035
[INAUDIBLE]

00:38:43.035 --> 00:38:44.035
LUVVIE AJAYI: That's it.

00:38:44.035 --> 00:38:44.770
ROLAND MARTIN: I'm
