VINT CERF: Point of order.

00:58:27.380 --> 00:58:27.800
EDDIE HUANG: I don't
think that's too

00:58:27.800 --> 00:58:28.850
expensive for Google.

00:58:28.850 --> 00:58:29.210
ROLAND MARTIN: Oh,
that's for Vint.

00:58:29.210 --> 00:58:30.450
That was for Vint.

00:58:30.450 --> 00:58:31.533
VINT CERF: Point of order.

00:58:31.533 --> 00:58:32.420
It's not the DOJ.

00:58:32.420 --> 00:58:34.010
It's the Department
of Labor that

00:58:34.010 --> 00:58:36.320
is asking for the statistics.

00:58:36.320 --> 00:58:39.530
And apparently, we have
given them an enormous amount

00:58:39.530 --> 00:58:41.570
of statistical information.

00:58:41.570 --> 00:58:44.840
We even have data that shows
that when we hire women,

00:58:44.840 --> 00:58:48.252
they get higher pay raises
than the men do in order

00:58:48.252 --> 00:58:49.710
to adjust for the
fact that they've

00:58:49.710 --> 00:58:51.650
been historically underpaid.

00:58:51.650 --> 00:58:53.510
So there's a lot of
evidence that Google

00:58:53.510 --> 00:58:57.350
has done a great deal to
even out these things.

00:58:57.350 --> 00:59:01.025
It's built in now to our
algorithms for raises

00:59:01.025 --> 00:59:01.900
and things like that.

00:59:01.900 --> 00:59:03.605
It's now algorithmically built.

00:59:03.605 --> 00:59:05.980
EDDIE HUANG: You've got a
snitch in your company, though.

00:59:05.980 --> 00:59:07.689
[LAUGHING]

00:59:07.689 --> 00:59:08.980
ROLAND MARTIN: Paola, go ahead.

00:59:08.980 --> 00:59:11.031
[INAUDIBLE] out here snitching.

00:59:11.031 --> 00:59:13.405
PAOLA MENDOZA: I think-- this
is what I like to advocate,

00:59:13.405 --> 00:59:16.430
and this is what I do
on my own personal life.

00:59:16.430 --> 00:59:18.939
I think we just need to
share how much we make.

00:59:18.939 --> 00:59:19.730
LUVVIE AJAYI: Word.

00:59:19.730 --> 00:59:20.522
PAOLA MENDOZA: Women,
you just need to go up,

00:59:20.522 --> 00:59:21.950
and you need to
ask your coworker,

00:59:21.950 --> 00:59:23.530
hey, how much do you make?

00:59:23.530 --> 00:59:25.010
This is what I make.

00:59:25.010 --> 00:59:26.570
I'm just saying.

00:59:26.570 --> 00:59:30.000
I'm just saying.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.350
We as women and as
people of color,

00:59:33.350 --> 00:59:35.450
need to share
information because when

00:59:35.450 --> 00:59:38.150
we have information, we
can then empower ourselves

00:59:38.150 --> 00:59:39.660
from a place of knowledge.

00:59:39.660 --> 00:59:41.060
And it's as simple as that.

00:59:41.060 --> 00:59:43.320
Break down that barrier
and ask the question.

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:45.650
And men, be up front
with your coworker.

00:59:45.650 --> 00:59:48.050
And you can go up to her,
him, too, and say, hey,

00:59:48.050 --> 00:59:49.410
I make this amount of money.

00:59:49.410 --> 00:59:49.750
How much do you make?

00:59:49.750 --> 00:59:52.250
EDDIE HUANG: I would pull up
to the club with my tax return,

00:59:52.250 --> 00:59:54.410
if that was socially acceptable.

00:59:54.410 --> 00:59:56.412
You feel me?

00:59:56.412 --> 00:59:57.620
ROLAND MARTIN: Next question.

00:59:57.620 --> 01:00:00.230
"I recently had a
conversation with a friend who

01:00:00.230 --> 01:00:03.770
insisted racism, sexism is no
longer a problem in America,

01:00:03.770 --> 01:00:08.220
that America is the least
racist country in the world."

01:00:08.220 --> 01:00:11.750
Parentheses, "It was a baffling
and frustrating conversation,

01:00:11.750 --> 01:00:13.475
no doubt.

01:00:13.475 --> 01:00:15.410
Does the panel have
suggestions for how

01:00:15.410 --> 01:00:17.600
to get people to rethink
this misconception?"

01:00:17.600 --> 01:00:19.900
One person, who
wants to take it?

01:00:19.900 --> 01:00:20.900
LUVVIE AJAYI: I'd probably
stop being friends with them,

01:00:20.900 --> 01:00:23.233
because I'm like you just so
out of-- just out of touch.

01:00:23.233 --> 01:00:24.580
Just, I can't.

01:00:24.580 --> 01:00:26.000
I mean, where do you go?

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.154
So when you're having a
discussion with somebody,

01:00:28.154 --> 01:00:29.820
the point is to have
this middle ground.

01:00:29.820 --> 01:00:31.920
But when you're over here,
and the person's over here,

01:00:31.920 --> 01:00:32.970
how do you come to
the middle with that?

01:00:32.970 --> 01:00:34.969
VINT CERF: That's what
you've been trying to do.

01:00:34.969 --> 01:00:37.820
And both of you have said
that you're trying to find--

01:00:37.820 --> 01:00:41.600
the trick was to get away
from the racist discussion

01:00:41.600 --> 01:00:44.610
and get to something
more specific.

01:00:44.610 --> 01:00:46.340
Because, in fact,
whatever it was

01:00:46.340 --> 01:00:48.590
might not actually have
been a racist issue at all,

01:00:48.590 --> 01:00:49.610
it might have been
something else.

01:00:49.610 --> 01:00:50.880
But finding something concrete.

01:00:50.880 --> 01:00:51.910
LUVVIE AJAYI: But this person
said it's no longer a problem.

01:00:51.910 --> 01:00:54.200
This person said racism
and sexism is no longer

01:00:54.200 --> 01:00:55.860
a problem in America,
and that America

01:00:55.860 --> 01:00:57.669
is the least racist country.

01:00:57.669 --> 01:00:58.960
How do you talk to that person?

01:00:58.960 --> 01:01:01.293
EDDIE HUANG: When someone is
like that out to lunch, out

01:01:01.293 --> 01:01:04.190
to sea, I'm just like, please
tell me how you got here.

01:01:04.190 --> 01:01:05.240
Just tell me more.

01:01:05.240 --> 01:01:07.760
Like we said, I just
want to hear more.

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:08.900
VINT CERF: Just ask--

01:01:08.900 --> 01:01:10.608
ROLAND MARTIN: I think
in that situation,

01:01:10.608 --> 01:01:13.090
no matter how stupid
or crazy they are,

01:01:13.090 --> 01:01:15.668
you still force them to
say, OK, well, let's talk

01:01:15.668 --> 01:01:17.501
about the study that
showed that if you have

01:01:17.501 --> 01:01:21.230
a black sounding name, you have
50% less likelihood of getting

01:01:21.230 --> 01:01:23.830
a return phone call for a
job than if you were white,

01:01:23.830 --> 01:01:25.619
when it is the
exact same resume.

01:01:25.619 --> 01:01:27.160
LUVVIE AJAYI: They
will find excuses.

01:01:27.160 --> 01:01:28.340
ROLAND MARTIN: No, but
here's the deal though.

01:01:28.340 --> 01:01:30.290
In my experience, in
hitting people every day

01:01:30.290 --> 01:01:34.750
with questions, you begin to hit
folks with specific questions

01:01:34.750 --> 01:01:36.680
and data, it's hard to ignore.

01:01:36.680 --> 01:01:38.330
The problem, I
think, in that case,

01:01:38.330 --> 01:01:40.665
is when you have
general conversation.

01:01:40.665 --> 01:01:42.040
When you hit them
with specifics,

01:01:42.040 --> 01:01:43.831
it's a little harder
for them to wiggle out

01:01:43.831 --> 01:01:46.760
because they have to justify how
that forms with their opinion.

01:01:46.760 --> 01:01:47.260
Question.

01:01:49.814 --> 01:01:51.230
AUDIENCE: On the
panel there, they

01:01:51.230 --> 01:01:54.670
talked about how there's like
two ends of the spectrum,

01:01:54.670 --> 01:01:55.420
right?

01:01:55.420 --> 01:01:57.920
You have one person that
could be called a racist,

01:01:57.920 --> 01:01:59.750
and then another
person who disagrees.

01:01:59.750 --> 01:02:03.840
And then the meat of
the issue gets lost.

01:02:03.840 --> 01:02:06.080
When I think about a
lot of these things,

01:02:06.080 --> 01:02:08.930
there's a lot of facts
that are hitting history.

01:02:08.930 --> 01:02:11.450
And as you stood on the stage,
and you were reading out

01:02:11.450 --> 01:02:13.490
lots of facts, I
was just like, wow,

01:02:13.490 --> 01:02:15.154
because not a lot
of people know that.

01:02:15.154 --> 01:02:16.820
ROLAND MARTIN: Because
they didn't read.

01:02:16.820 --> 01:02:18.200
AUDIENCE: They
didn't read, and I

01:02:18.200 --> 01:02:19.824
didn't grow up in this country.

01:02:19.824 --> 01:02:20.740
LUVVIE AJAYI: Nigeria?

01:02:20.740 --> 01:02:21.981
AUDIENCE: Like Luvvie--

01:02:21.981 --> 01:02:24.022
LUVVIE AJAYI: I knew you
were a Nigeria man, yes.

01:02:24.022 --> 01:02:25.920
VINT CERF: You recognized that.

01:02:25.920 --> 01:02:27.170
LUVVIE AJAYI: I saw my people.

01:02:30.810 --> 01:02:32.100
AUDIENCE: I came to the USA.

01:02:32.100 --> 01:02:34.090
I took an African-American
culture class,

01:02:34.090 --> 01:02:37.560
and I was just amazed at a lot
of things that are in history,

01:02:37.560 --> 01:02:39.430
but again, are lost
to a lot of people.

01:02:39.430 --> 01:02:41.940
ROLAND MARTIN: There's
history, and there's his-story.

01:02:41.940 --> 01:02:43.190
Two different meanings.

01:02:43.190 --> 01:02:44.540
True.

01:02:44.540 --> 01:02:47.040
And I know the writer
Ta-Nesisi Coates,

01:02:47.040 --> 01:02:48.780
and he wrote that
magnificent essay.

01:02:48.780 --> 01:02:51.270
And again, so much facts in
there that not a lot of people

01:02:51.270 --> 01:02:51.770
know.

01:02:51.770 --> 01:02:54.800
So how do you get those
facts out there to people?

01:02:54.800 --> 01:02:57.050
Because at the end of the
day, we're all human beings.

01:02:57.050 --> 01:02:57.970
And that's what
we're trying to do.

01:02:57.970 --> 01:02:59.990
Because you can't
force people to love.

01:02:59.990 --> 01:03:02.150
VINT CERF: I have an
unfortunate observation

01:03:02.150 --> 01:03:04.120
to make about the
American culture.

01:03:04.120 --> 01:03:04.270
ROLAND MARTIN: Thank you.

01:03:04.270 --> 01:03:04.380
Go, go.

01:03:04.380 --> 01:03:05.171
We got two minutes.

01:03:05.171 --> 01:03:10.040
VINT CERF: The American
culture tends to have amnesia.

01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:13.730
If you visit in Europe, there
will be casual conversation

01:03:13.730 --> 01:03:19.340
in which the years 1400
and 1066 and 1622 and 1648

01:03:19.340 --> 01:03:22.160
are regularly mentioned
as if they were yesterday.

01:03:22.160 --> 01:03:25.320
In America, you can't remember
what happened two weeks ago.

01:03:25.320 --> 01:03:28.930
And so we have cultural, really
serious cultural problems

01:03:28.930 --> 01:03:30.705
remembering facts and history.

01:03:30.705 --> 01:03:32.080
And I don't know
how to fix that.

01:03:32.080 --> 01:03:32.840
ROLAND MARTIN: Well,
part of the problem

01:03:32.840 --> 01:03:35.090
is that we have not actually
had real American history

01:03:35.090 --> 01:03:36.650
in our schools.

01:03:36.650 --> 01:03:40.254
That's why I say history
and his-story, that's real.

01:03:40.254 --> 01:03:41.670
And so there's so
many things that

01:03:41.670 --> 01:03:43.450
are actually being left out.

01:03:43.450 --> 01:03:48.590
And so for me, I use my
media platforms to do it,

01:03:48.590 --> 01:03:53.530
every single day, in terms
of I got #rolandbookclub.

01:03:53.530 --> 01:03:56.356
So people ask me, dude, how
you know all this other stuff?

01:03:56.356 --> 01:03:57.980
These are all the
books that I've read.

01:03:57.980 --> 01:04:00.850
Then they're like, OK,
man, I understand now.

01:04:00.850 --> 01:04:07.424
And so, we also have to
make history accessible

01:04:07.424 --> 01:04:09.340
and explain it in a way--
you got to remember,

01:04:09.340 --> 01:04:12.760
newspapers, historically,
have taught us

01:04:12.760 --> 01:04:14.580
write on a fifth grade level.

01:04:14.580 --> 01:04:16.800
It may sound crazy.

01:04:16.800 --> 01:04:18.749
But you write on a
fifth grade level.

01:04:18.749 --> 01:04:21.040
And so to understand, and
literally, I was on the radio

01:04:21.040 --> 01:04:23.650
today, and they were trying
to talk about economics,

01:04:23.650 --> 01:04:26.180
and I said, OK, let me
just walk you through.

01:04:26.180 --> 01:04:29.830
1619 to 1863, 244
years of slavery.

01:04:29.830 --> 01:04:32.310
Two years of the war,
then you had, of course,

01:04:32.310 --> 01:04:36.760
end of the war, 1865 to 1877,
12 years of Reconstruction.

01:04:36.760 --> 01:04:39.840
Great Compromises of
1877 starts Jim Crow.

01:04:39.840 --> 01:04:42.580
That goes through almost 1970.

01:04:42.580 --> 01:04:46.260
If you use the death of
King, April 4th, '68,

01:04:46.260 --> 01:04:48.250
then let's say
another two years,

01:04:48.250 --> 01:04:51.490
so if you say 1970
is the marker where

01:04:51.490 --> 01:04:55.510
black folks were technically
fully free Americans, that's

01:04:55.510 --> 01:04:57.680
only 47.

01:04:57.680 --> 01:04:59.320
Only 47 years.

01:04:59.320 --> 01:05:02.320
When people hear that,
they go, whoa, hold on.

01:05:02.320 --> 01:05:03.271
That's it?

01:05:03.271 --> 01:05:05.770
Then you say yes, the first
wave of black and blue corporate

01:05:05.770 --> 01:05:08.059
America happened
in the early '70s.

01:05:08.059 --> 01:05:09.850
The first African-Americans
on Wall Street,

01:05:09.850 --> 01:05:12.240
in terms of Morgan
Stanley, those companies.

01:05:12.240 --> 01:05:15.010
Then the first African-Americans
in major Ivy League

01:05:15.010 --> 01:05:15.910
institutions.

01:05:15.910 --> 01:05:17.670
Now all of the sudden--

01:05:17.670 --> 01:05:20.230
then I say, I'll
be 49 in November.

01:05:20.230 --> 01:05:20.980
LUVVIE AJAYI: Wow.

01:05:20.980 --> 01:05:24.130
ROLAND MARTIN: Which means
I was born into an America

01:05:24.130 --> 01:05:26.090
where I was not fully free.

01:05:26.090 --> 01:05:28.570
Which means-- I
don't have any kids--

01:05:28.570 --> 01:05:32.380
my nieces and nephews
are the first generation

01:05:32.380 --> 01:05:38.770
of African-Americans born
technically fully free.

01:05:38.770 --> 01:05:42.010
Now people go, damn.

01:05:42.010 --> 01:05:46.570
Because they think
slavery, 1863, and totally

01:05:46.570 --> 01:05:48.910
ignore the fact
that we literally

01:05:48.910 --> 01:05:51.640
were frozen out of
economic systems

01:05:51.640 --> 01:05:54.790
through the 1960s to 1970.

01:05:54.790 --> 01:05:57.170
But again, it's getting people
to break it down that way.

01:05:57.170 --> 01:06:01.450
Then they go, whoa,
as opposed to just,

01:06:01.450 --> 01:06:03.400
oh, slavery ended at this time.

01:06:03.400 --> 01:06:05.810
Because people really,
they just don't know.

01:06:05.810 --> 01:06:11.020
Even a whole lot of black
people have no idea, no clue.

01:06:11.020 --> 01:06:12.610
EDDIE HUANG: You
mentioned Dr. King.

01:06:12.610 --> 01:06:14.670
You asked the question about--

01:06:14.670 --> 01:06:17.680
you asked the question about
we have all these facts,

01:06:17.680 --> 01:06:21.280
yet it seems like people don't
want to listen or give credence

01:06:21.280 --> 01:06:22.000
to these facts.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:26.860
And I think Dr. King's works,
it really tells you the most

01:06:26.860 --> 01:06:28.062
and gives you the blueprint.

01:06:28.062 --> 01:06:29.770
"Letter from Birmingham
Jail" is probably

01:06:29.770 --> 01:06:31.990
the most analytical essay
that Dr. King wrote.

01:06:31.990 --> 01:06:34.210
It breaks things down
systematically with facts,

01:06:34.210 --> 01:06:37.030
and it's written
to intellectuals.

01:06:37.030 --> 01:06:38.200
But his most powerful--

01:06:38.200 --> 01:06:38.840
ROLAND MARTIN:
Actually, it was written

01:06:38.840 --> 01:06:40.660
to white pastors in Birmingham.

01:06:40.660 --> 01:06:43.600
EDDIE HUANG: Yes,
intellectuals, yes.

01:06:43.600 --> 01:06:47.100
So his most powerful
speech, though,

01:06:47.100 --> 01:06:50.690
and the most persuasive speech,
undeniably, is I Have a Dream.

01:06:50.690 --> 01:06:52.780
And that is a persuasive speech.

01:06:52.780 --> 01:06:55.570
And I think that all of
us have to acknowledge,

01:06:55.570 --> 01:06:57.700
it's not just enough
to be right if we

01:06:57.700 --> 01:07:00.010
want the result that we desire.

01:07:00.010 --> 01:07:01.470
We have to be persuasive.

01:07:01.470 --> 01:07:05.350
ROLAND MARTIN: But don't
just read the bottom one

01:07:05.350 --> 01:07:06.600
third of the speech.

01:07:06.600 --> 01:07:09.100
First all, it was never even
called "I Have a Dream" speech.

01:07:09.100 --> 01:07:10.660
It was called
"Normalcy No More."

01:07:10.660 --> 01:07:11.470
EDDIE HUANG: I understand this.

01:07:11.470 --> 01:07:12.190
But you're talking to me
like I don't know the facts--

01:07:12.190 --> 01:07:13.250
ROLAND MARTIN: No, no, no.

01:07:13.250 --> 01:07:14.960
I'm saying it to other
folks in the room.

01:07:14.960 --> 01:07:15.465
Here's why.

01:07:15.465 --> 01:07:16.840
LUVVIE AJAYI: Come
on, knowledge.

01:07:16.840 --> 01:07:18.670
ROLAND MARTIN:
Because every year,

01:07:18.670 --> 01:07:22.990
we replay the King's speech, and
we replay the "I Have a Dream"

01:07:22.990 --> 01:07:24.010
part.

01:07:24.010 --> 01:07:26.680
We don't talk about
the top two thirds,

01:07:26.680 --> 01:07:29.440
where he talked about police
brutality, economic inequality,

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:31.900
bank of injustice, because
"I Have a Dream" part

01:07:31.900 --> 01:07:32.890
is all nice and feely.

01:07:32.890 --> 01:07:34.420
EDDIE HUANG: What does
that tell you, Roland?

01:07:34.420 --> 01:07:36.175
LUVVIE AJAYI: It makes him
the patron saint of good times

01:07:36.175 --> 01:07:37.130
and nonviolence.

01:07:37.130 --> 01:07:37.440
ROLAND MARTIN: Right.

01:07:37.440 --> 01:07:38.140
LUVVIE AJAYI: That's
what that makes him.

01:07:38.140 --> 01:07:39.770
ROLAND MARTIN: We turned
King into a bobblehead--

01:07:39.770 --> 01:07:40.570
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yes.

01:07:40.570 --> 01:07:43.050
ROLAND MARTIN: As opposed
to a radical revolutionary

01:07:43.050 --> 01:07:43.890
that he was.

01:07:43.890 --> 01:07:44.210
LUVVIE AJAYI: Exactly.

01:07:44.210 --> 01:07:45.960
ROLAND MARTIN: So the
challenge to anybody

01:07:45.960 --> 01:07:49.030
in the room is, don't leave here
just reading the bottom part,

01:07:49.030 --> 01:07:51.280
start from the
beginning, and then go,

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:53.675
whoa, dude was slaying
folks, and not holding hands.

01:07:53.675 --> 01:07:56.050
EDDIE HUANG: Of course, but
do you think that he would be

01:07:56.050 --> 01:07:57.285
as productive and persuasive--

01:07:57.285 --> 01:07:58.618
LUVVIE AJAYI: And assassinated--

01:07:58.618 --> 01:08:01.540
EDDIE HUANG: --and
create all the progress

01:08:01.540 --> 01:08:04.360
that he did if he
was not smart enough

01:08:04.360 --> 01:08:05.949
to be persuasive as well?

01:08:05.949 --> 01:08:07.490
ROLAND MARTIN: No,
he was persuasive.

01:08:07.490 --> 01:08:08.320
EDDIE HUANG: He was a genius.

01:08:08.320 --> 01:08:09.790
ROLAND MARTIN: He was a
radical revolutionary.

01:08:09.790 --> 01:08:10.930
EDDIE HUANG: He did it all.

01:08:10.930 --> 01:08:14.350
He was a five tool player,
like persuasive and analytical.

01:08:14.350 --> 01:08:16.600
And you can't just keep
telling people read the facts,

01:08:16.600 --> 01:08:17.474
read this, read this.

01:08:17.474 --> 01:08:19.420
They're not-- a lot of
people aren't going to.

01:08:19.420 --> 01:08:20.503
You have to persuade them.

01:08:20.503 --> 01:08:21.939
They need sugar
with the medicine.

01:08:21.939 --> 01:08:23.319
ROLAND MARTIN: But what
we've done, though, is--

01:08:23.319 --> 01:08:24.943
this is why I disagree
with you, Eddie.

01:08:24.943 --> 01:08:27.250
What we've done is,
we've only given America

01:08:27.250 --> 01:08:30.460
the I Have a Dream part, because
that's the hand-holding part.

01:08:30.460 --> 01:08:31.210
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yes.

01:08:31.210 --> 01:08:33.069
ROLAND MARTIN: See,
the top, that's

01:08:33.069 --> 01:08:35.439
the equivalent of
listening to a sermon,

01:08:35.439 --> 01:08:37.510
and you cheering, but you
skipped the scripture.

01:08:37.510 --> 01:08:39.640
EDDIE HUANG: I'm not telling
you to skip the rest,

01:08:39.640 --> 01:08:42.099
I'm telling you to
Trojan horse people.

01:08:42.099 --> 01:08:44.390
ROLAND MARTIN: But I want
them to read the whole thing.

01:08:44.390 --> 01:08:45.010
EDDIE HUANG: You
ever gone fishing

01:08:45.010 --> 01:08:46.260
without something on the hook?

01:08:46.260 --> 01:08:48.326
ROLAND MARTIN: I hate fishing.

01:08:48.326 --> 01:08:50.220
Damn it, I'm going
to the supermarket

01:08:50.220 --> 01:08:51.740
to buy some catfish.

01:08:51.740 --> 01:08:53.710
Blend, what's up?

01:08:53.710 --> 01:08:56.260
AUDIENCE: My name is Tsvi,
and I was curious what the--

01:08:56.260 --> 01:08:57.729
ROLAND MARTIN: Spell that.

01:08:57.729 --> 01:08:58.969
AUDIENCE: T-S-V-I.

01:08:58.969 --> 01:09:00.760
ROLAND MARTIN: I would
have never got that.

01:09:00.760 --> 01:09:02.801
EDDIE HUANG: I've seen
your graffiti around town.

01:09:02.801 --> 01:09:05.649
AUDIENCE: Oh, yeah,
that's my tag.

01:09:05.649 --> 01:09:10.540
So my question is about protests
on college campuses being

01:09:10.540 --> 01:09:11.640
shut down.

01:09:11.640 --> 01:09:15.850
Sorry, speakers being shut
down because of protests.

01:09:15.850 --> 01:09:19.660
Not just like people asking
good questions at the end,

01:09:19.660 --> 01:09:21.943
or making a little
noise at the beginning,

01:09:21.943 --> 01:09:23.359
but then letting
the person speak.

01:09:23.359 --> 01:09:25.650
I'm talking about fully
shutting down speakers

01:09:25.650 --> 01:09:27.340
like at Middlebury or Berkeley.

01:09:27.340 --> 01:09:29.580
And I was just curious
what, you know--

01:09:29.580 --> 01:09:33.180
I understand it's a very
nuanced, complicated issue.

01:09:33.180 --> 01:09:34.569
But I was curious--

01:09:34.569 --> 01:09:36.401
VINT CERF: It's not
complicated at all.

01:09:36.401 --> 01:09:37.359
AUDIENCE: Thanks a lot.

01:09:37.359 --> 01:09:39.109
VINT CERF: This is not
complicated at all.

01:09:39.109 --> 01:09:41.410
This is an incredible
erosion of what

01:09:41.410 --> 01:09:44.620
should be a serious freedom
of speech on the campuses.

01:09:44.620 --> 01:09:47.890
I think it's outrageous
that students do that,

01:09:47.890 --> 01:09:50.040
because the whole key
here, and the thing

01:09:50.040 --> 01:09:52.870
we've been talking
about all this session

01:09:52.870 --> 01:09:56.890
is about the conversations that
we have to have on tough topics

01:09:56.890 --> 01:09:59.080
where there's real
serious disagreement.

01:09:59.080 --> 01:10:01.840
And hearing the other side is
an important part of all that.

01:10:01.840 --> 01:10:04.480
So I think it's outrageous
that the campuses have

01:10:04.480 --> 01:10:06.190
been forced to do this.

01:10:06.190 --> 01:10:08.450
ROLAND MARTIN: Stupid and
asinine, that's what it is.

01:10:08.450 --> 01:10:09.564
No, it is.

01:10:09.564 --> 01:10:11.730
Because what happens when
someone wants to shut down

01:10:11.730 --> 01:10:12.760
a speaker you like?

01:10:12.760 --> 01:10:14.090
PAOLA MENDOZA: Which
is happening right now

01:10:14.090 --> 01:10:14.881
with Linda Sarsour.

01:10:14.881 --> 01:10:17.440
So Linda Sarsour is the
commencement speaker at CUNY,

01:10:17.440 --> 01:10:20.230
and the right wing has
taken it up to try and shut

01:10:20.230 --> 01:10:21.940
her down because
she's a Muslim woman,

01:10:21.940 --> 01:10:23.470
and they claim a lot of things.

01:10:23.470 --> 01:10:25.440
And I know Linda
personally very well,

01:10:25.440 --> 01:10:26.710
that are completely not true.

01:10:26.710 --> 01:10:28.530
So there are protests.

01:10:28.530 --> 01:10:30.520
There's an online
campaign against her.

01:10:30.520 --> 01:10:32.530
And that is someone
that we want speaking.

01:10:32.530 --> 01:10:35.150
And that is someone that I
believe in what she's saying.

01:10:35.150 --> 01:10:39.170
So I agree that it's not
a difficult question.

01:10:39.170 --> 01:10:40.670
Speakers should be
allowed to speak.

01:10:40.670 --> 01:10:42.220
ROLAND MARTIN: Final comment.

01:10:42.220 --> 01:10:44.810
The one thing you want
people leaving here with,

01:10:44.810 --> 01:10:45.970
moving forward.

01:10:45.970 --> 01:10:49.327
30 seconds, go.

01:10:49.327 --> 01:10:51.160
LUVVIE AJAYI: Just
challenge your own ideas,

01:10:51.160 --> 01:10:53.365
and also read beyond the
"I Have a Dream" speech.

01:10:53.365 --> 01:10:55.240
I'm really glad you
actually brought that up.

01:10:55.240 --> 01:10:57.840
Because MLK Day comes
and everyone share's

01:10:57.840 --> 01:11:00.820
the exact same quotes, of
him being this pacifist,

01:11:00.820 --> 01:11:03.040
like yeah, we just
all need to unite.

01:11:03.040 --> 01:11:06.030
No, like, before he
even got to that dude,

01:11:06.030 --> 01:11:08.780
and even as his
politics went further,

01:11:08.780 --> 01:11:10.090
he got even more radical.

01:11:10.090 --> 01:11:12.070
So for all the
historical figures,

01:11:12.070 --> 01:11:14.740
you hear about Rosa Parks
sitting on the bus, read deeper

01:11:14.740 --> 01:11:17.940
about these same bobbleheads
that you keep seeing

01:11:17.940 --> 01:11:19.897
in social media as buttons.

01:11:19.897 --> 01:11:21.730
And realize what they
were saying back then,

01:11:21.730 --> 01:11:22.690
because I feel like
there's something

01:11:22.690 --> 01:11:23.815
we need to learn from them.

01:11:23.815 --> 01:11:25.180
There's a lot of things.

01:11:25.180 --> 01:11:26.596
PAOLA MENDOZA: I
want to challenge

01:11:26.596 --> 01:11:28.900
everyone here and listening
to have a conversation that

01:11:28.900 --> 01:11:33.190
makes your heart pound, that
makes your palms sweaty.

01:11:33.190 --> 01:11:36.996
And do that and be OK in that
feeling of uncomfortability

01:11:36.996 --> 01:11:39.370
and knowing that when you get
to the other side, whatever

01:11:39.370 --> 01:11:41.770
that conversation is about,
that you're going to be OK.

01:11:41.770 --> 01:11:44.311
And during that conversation--
and this is the most important

01:11:44.311 --> 01:11:44.860
thing--

01:11:44.860 --> 01:11:47.050
is that you have to
listen to understand, not

01:11:47.050 --> 01:11:48.810
listen to be right.

01:11:48.810 --> 01:11:49.810
And so, do that.

01:11:49.810 --> 01:11:50.770
Do that this week.

01:11:50.770 --> 01:11:52.000
Go have that conversation.

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:52.875
ROLAND MARTIN: Eddie?

01:11:55.637 --> 01:11:57.220
EDDIE HUANG: Despite
all the stupidity

01:11:57.220 --> 01:12:00.430
I see on an everyday basis,
I'm bullish on humanity,

01:12:00.430 --> 01:12:02.770
and I do think that it's
going to get better.

01:12:02.770 --> 01:12:03.840
ROLAND MARTIN: Vint?

01:12:03.840 --> 01:12:05.381
VINT CERF: For the
Google people that

01:12:05.381 --> 01:12:07.230
are here, take the
unconscious bias

01:12:07.230 --> 01:12:08.840
test if you haven't already.

01:12:08.840 --> 01:12:12.640
You will be just shocked to
discover that you have them.

01:12:12.640 --> 01:12:13.916
You just don't know that yet.

01:12:13.916 --> 01:12:16.290
ROLAND MARTIN: I created this
hashtag just playing around

01:12:16.290 --> 01:12:19.700
called #teamwhipdatass.

01:12:19.700 --> 01:12:20.450
LUVVIE AJAYI: Why?

01:12:20.450 --> 01:12:21.450
Why is Roland like this?

01:12:21.450 --> 01:12:23.350
ROLAND MARTIN: Well,
I did, team, whip--

01:12:23.350 --> 01:12:29.740
W-H-I-P, dat-- D-A-T, A-S-S.
Y'all think I'm lying,

01:12:29.740 --> 01:12:31.330
look it up.

01:12:31.330 --> 01:12:35.910
Every day I wake up
ready to do battle.

01:12:35.910 --> 01:12:38.890
Every day I have
breath, I believe

01:12:38.890 --> 01:12:43.210
that I could flip
somebody on a given issue.

01:12:43.210 --> 01:12:44.750
I don't why from a fight.

01:12:44.750 --> 01:12:46.600
I don't back down from a battle.

01:12:46.600 --> 01:12:48.010
I'll debate you.

01:12:48.010 --> 01:12:50.370
It might be rough,
it might be soft.

01:12:50.370 --> 01:12:51.370
It might easy.

01:12:51.370 --> 01:12:52.710
It might be hand-holding.

01:12:52.710 --> 01:12:55.129
Or I might have
to whoop your ass.

01:12:55.129 --> 01:12:56.920
But that really is the
attitude that I have

01:12:56.920 --> 01:13:02.170
because if people of conscience
take a day off and run

01:13:02.170 --> 01:13:06.430
from the fight, then
ignorance always wins.

01:13:06.430 --> 01:13:08.983
And the last thing
is, I'm never going

01:13:08.983 --> 01:13:11.980
to let somebody else know
more information than I do,

01:13:11.980 --> 01:13:14.650
so I'm going to read as much
as I can, so when they lie,

01:13:14.650 --> 01:13:16.674
I can bust them
every single time.

01:13:16.674 --> 01:13:17.590
Thanks a bunch, y'all.

01:13:17.590 --> 01:13:19.390
Give it up for our panel.

01:13:19.390 --> 01:13:20.590
EDDIE HUANG: Thanks, Roland.

01:13:20.590 --> 01:13:25.440
[APPLAUSE]

